	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Costs of the CARIFORUM EPA claimed in study to be ‘modest’</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A report, ‘The Economic Partnership Agreement: Towards a new era for Caribbean trade’ has been jointly published by the Caribbean Policy Research Institute (CaPRI) with the Centre for International Governance Innovation (CIGI). According to Caribbean think-tank CaPRI, ‘the aggregate negative impact of the EPA on Caribbean states will be modest, although it will likely produce challenges for smaller Caribbean governments.’ The report concludes that to make the transition to the EPA successfully, the region’s governments ‘will have to put aside their policy differences and aim for more effective policy coordination in the interests of future development,’ and that ‘Caribbean integration has been hindered, not by structural arrangements which the EPA will now alter, but by lax movement in that direction by Caribbean governments.’</p><p>The claims about the economic and tax effects of the EPA are based on a 2009 study by CaPRI which focused on Jamaica, St. Lucia, Trinidad and Tobago, and Guyana. Only the headline results from this research are presented in the new paper which, consequently, does not itself offer any detailed evidence to support its findings about the limited aggregate negative effects. But what the report does provide is a fluent contribution to the lively debate in the CARIFORUM region (and more widely) about the economic and fiscal effects of the EPAs. Critics of the EPA have already responded, arguing that neither the 2009 study nor the present paper addresses in any substantive way their principal concerns. These, according to respected Caribbean academic Norman Girvan, are ‘mostly of a long-term and strategic nature, relate to the alleged development-enhancing effects of the EPA and its implications for regional integration, policy space, the direction of the region’s development and the domino effect on the region’s international trade negotiations.’</p><p>In a section of the CaPRI report on what the authors call ‘the implementation dilemma’, they argue that ‘making the necessary changes to extant legislation will be a huge task for Caribbean countries’ but that ‘translating the agreement into feasible opportunities for Caribbean producers to access the European market and to realise the producer and consumer effects that the agreement should usher in’ could prove to be an even more formidable task.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Caribbean Policy Research Institute/Centre for International Governance Innovation, ‘The Economic Partnership Agreement: Towards a new era for Caribbean trade’, Report No. R-10-002, September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.capricaribbean.org/research/economic-partnership-agreement-towards-new-era-caribbean-trade" target="_self">http://www.capricaribbean.org/research/economic-partnership-agreement-to...</a></p><p>Caribbean Policy Research Institute (CaPRI), ‘The impact of the EPA on Caribbean economies: A structural analysis’,<i>&nbsp;</i>November 2009.</p><p>
<a href="http://www.capricaribbean.org/research/impact-epa-caribbean-economies" target="_self">http://www.capricaribbean.org/research/impact-epa-caribbean-economies</a></p><p><i>Normangirvan.info</i>, ‘The CIGI-CaPRI paper on the CARIFORUM EPA: a comment, Norman Girvan’, 22 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.normangirvan.info/the-cigi-capri-paper-on-the-cariforum-epa-a-comment-norman-girvan/" target="_self">http://www.normangirvan.info/the-cigi-capri-paper-on-the-cariforum-epa-a...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The controversy to which the EPAs have given rise is well reflected in the CaPRI paper, which addresses the critics head on and, in some cases, argues that their claims are exaggerated or false. Although the controversy will never be ‘resolved’ (given that some differences are philosophical and all economic forecasts involve assumptions that can be challenged), the area of disagreement may shrink as more empirical studies are undertaken based on what was actually agreed and is being implemented. Several such <i>ex post </i>studies have already been completed (one of which is the CaPRI 2009 report), but both the EPA and the CARIFORUM region are enormously complicated, and much more remains to be done. One example of this is that basic information is missing for most of the CARIFORUM states, such as the extent of the initial tariff cut required when the EPA entered into force, and which countries have yet made these cuts. At the time that the EPA was initialled, supporters claimed that the tariff levels to be applied on entry into force were almost the same as those already in force. But this seemed improbable for some countries, and it was not possible to check it at the time, as the published tariff levels were at least one year out of date.</p><p>The CaPRI report also directs attention to an important factor that will determine the impact of the EPA – implementation. The EPA will have an impact on the ground only as, when, and to the extent that its provisions are translated into new legislation or regulations, and these are applied in practice. Although the EPA was initialled in 2007, it is unclear how many of the region’s initial commitments have yet been implemented. Moreover, any improved CARIFORUM export access will produce gains only if the private sector is able to take advantage of them. This will depend not only on regional supply capacity but also the treatment accorded to competitors.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
